{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S4 — Review-bot identity + event delivery + LLM-Review voter (the proven pipe)\n\n## Why\nClose the loop: on a new patchset the rebar MCP reviews the change and casts the\ndeterministic `LLM-Review` vote via REST. For d251 this proves the PIPE with a real\nvote; the full four-pass kernel reviewer + the real dogfood is **b744-WS6**, which plugs\ninto this same seam. The seam (bot identity, label contract, webhook→MCP→vote\ndata-flow) therefore becomes a long-lived contract future work depends on, so S4 pins\nit down explicitly even though its review payload is intentionally minimal. Because\nsubmit REQUIRES the `LLM-Review` vote, the gate is **fail-closed**: a missed event,\na dropped vote, or a broken voter only ever DELAYS review (the change stays\nunsubmittable) — it can never let an unreviewed change merge.\n\n## What\n- **Bot identity.** A dedicated Gerrit account for the bot in the built-in\n  `Service Users` group (thread isolation; SERVICE_USER accounts are excluded from\n  the attention set except on a negative vote — see derisk AC below); its HTTP auth\n  token stored in SSM Parameter Store under a fixed path (e.g. `/rebar/gerrit/bot-token`).\n  The EC2 instance role is granted **least-privilege** SSM read scoped to exactly\n  that parameter path (`ssm:GetParameter` on `arn:aws:ssm:<region>:<acct>:parameter/rebar/gerrit/*`),\n  **never** a `Resource:\"*\"` grant. `infra/gerrit/service-user.sh` is **idempotent**:\n  it checks for the existing account (`GET /a/accounts/gerrit-bot`) before creating,\n  and upserts the SSM parameter (`put-parameter --overwrite`) so a re-run during\n  re-provisioning does not create a duplicate account or orphan a token.\n- **Event delivery — two integrated paths, one voter code path.**\n  - *Push (primary):* install the `webhooks` plugin to POST `patchset-created` to the\n    MCP endpoint (the HTTP-reachable MCP from S2). The webhook is **authenticated**: the\n    plugin is configured with a shared HMAC secret (stored in SSM alongside the bot token)\n    and the MCP voter VERIFIES the signature header on every inbound request, rejecting\n    unsigned / mismatched payloads — the vote endpoint cannot be driven by forged events.\n    (The endpoint is also not publicly routable beyond what nginx exposes for `/mcp/`.)\n  - *Backfill (safety net):* install the `events-log` plugin, which only **STORES** a\n    queryable event log (`GET /a/plugins/events-log/events?type=patchset-created&since=<checkpoint>`)\n    — it does NOT auto-replay missed webhooks. A named **reconciler** (`infra/mcp/reconcile.py`,\n    driven on MCP startup and on a configurable cron cadence, default 5 min) polls that\n    endpoint, identifies patchsets whose current revision carries **no** `LLM-Review`\n    vote (`GET /a/changes/{id}/revisions/current/votes`), and re-invokes the **same**\n    voter function the webhook path uses. It persists a last-processed checkpoint\n    (event timestamp/id) in a durable local file (or SSM) so it resumes incrementally;\n    the lookback window is configurable (default 24 h). Plugin jar provenance,\n    versions, and arm64 compatibility are confirmed by the derisk AC below before this\n    is wired.\n  - *Deduplication / idempotency (at-least-once delivery).* Both paths converge on one\n    idempotent voter. Before POSTing, the voter checks for an existing `LLM-Review`\n    vote on the current revision and **skips** if already present (and/or derives\n    `robot_run_id` deterministically from `change_id + revision_id` so Gerrit\n    deduplicates robot_comments). A webhook delivery and a backfill pass for the same\n    patchset therefore never produce a double vote or duplicate robot_comment threads.\n- **The vote.** The MCP voter casts `LLM-Review` via\n  `POST /a/changes/{id}/revisions/current/review` with `tag:autogenerated:rebar`,\n  `notify:NONE`, and a `robot_comments` payload. For the S4 **minimal-but-real**\n  shim the kernel may produce no file-anchored findings, so the voter posts a single\n  patchset-level robot_comment with `path:\"/PATCHSET_LEVEL\"` (Gerrit's synthetic\n  whole-patchset anchor; no `line`), a non-empty `message` (a fixed stub summary of\n  the deterministic outcome), and `robot_id` / `robot_run_id` / `url`. This keeps the\n  Gerrit payload structurally valid (a bare metadata `robot_comments` with no `path`\n  is a 400) and gives b744-WS6 a populated shape to extend.\n- **Verdict → label mapping (one-way-door contract; record in the ADR below).** The gate's\n  `finalize_verdict` (the orchestrator wrapping `review_kernel`) emits exactly **three\n  gate-level verdict strings** — `PASS`, `BLOCK`, `INDETERMINATE`. The voter maps THAT gate\n  verdict to the integer `LLM-Review` value, fail-closed (only `PASS` earns the\n  submit-enabling MAX; anything else, including `INDETERMINATE`, blocks). It does NOT map the\n  kernel's per-finding `pass3_decide` decisions (advisory/dropped) — those are internal to the\n  kernel and roll up INTO the gate verdict, not into the label:\n\n  | Gate verdict (`finalize_verdict`) | `LLM-Review` value | Effect |\n  |-----------------------------------|--------------------|--------|\n  | `PASS`          | `+MAX` (submit-enabling) | change becomes submittable |\n  | `BLOCK`         | `-1`               | change stays unsubmittable |\n  | `INDETERMINATE` | `-1` (fail-closed) | change stays unsubmittable |\n\n  The mapping (and the MAX value / label range, owned by d251 `project.config`) lives in a\n  **configurable** location (env var / SSM / a config file under `infra/mcp/`), not a\n  hardcoded constant, because b744-WS6 will change the scoring logic.\n- **Observability.** The voter emits structured JSON logs\n  (`timestamp, change_id, revision_id, vote_value, http_status, error`) to CloudWatch\n  Logs, and at least one CloudWatch alarm fires on a sustained voter error rate\n  (e.g. ≥3 failures in 5 min → SNS) so an expired token / down LLM / unreachable MCP\n  surfaces to an operator instead of silently stacking up unsubmittable changes.\n  Per the locked **freeze-and-restore, no-break-glass** posture, a persistently\n  unavailable voter leaves `main` frozen until the voter is RESTORED (fix the\n  MCP / LLM / token); there is deliberately NO script to disable the submit\n  requirement and merge unreviewed — that would defeat the gate. The alarm exists so\n  the freeze is noticed promptly.\n\n## Scope\nIn: bot account (idempotent + least-privilege SSM) + event plugins (push +\nevents-log-backed **reconciler**) + the voter call using a minimal-but-real review\npath + verdict→label mapping + dedup/idempotency + voter observability/alerting.\nSequencing within the ticket: (1) bot account + SSM token round-trip\nsmoke test (`curl /a/accounts/self`), THEN (2) plugins + webhook delivery to a stub,\nTHEN (3) wire the voter + reconciler and run the end-to-end ACs — so the riskiest\nREST/auth piece is validated before the full pipe is exercised.\nOut: the full four-pass kernel reviewer + overlays + dogfood (**b744-WS6**, which\nplugs into this seam); replication (S5). S4 deliberately keeps the review payload a\nstub and does NOT pull the kernel reviewer into this ticket.\n\n## Files\n- `infra/gerrit/service-user.sh` — idempotent bot-account creation + SSM token upsert,\n  plus the least-privilege instance-role SSM policy (or the IaC that defines it).\n- `infra/gerrit/webhooks.config` — `webhooks` plugin config (patchset-created → MCP).\n- `infra/mcp/` voter wiring — the thin `webhook → review → vote` shim (one idempotent\n  voter function) and `infra/mcp/reconcile.py` — the events-log poller/reconciler\n  (startup + cron) sharing that voter, with the verdict→label mapping config and\n  structured-logging/alarm wiring.\n- `docs/adr/0001-review-bot-pipe.md` — ADR recording the seam contract: bot-account\n  constraints (Service Users, attention-set behavior), the webhook→MCP→events-log\n  event boundary + dedup rule, the `LLM-Review` label/verdict→integer mapping, the\n  `robot_comments` shape, the SSM secret-naming convention, and the seam b744-WS6\n  must conform to.\n\n> Record `set_file_impact` ({path, reason}) for the files above before claiming, so\n> `next_batch` scheduling and the attestation are scoped to this work, and\n> `set_verify_commands` for the end-to-end checks below.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] **Happy-path vote (push).** On `patchset-created`, the bot casts an `LLM-Review`\n      vote via `POST /a/changes/{id}/revisions/current/review` with a structurally\n      valid `robot_comments` payload (`path:\"/PATCHSET_LEVEL\"`, non-empty `message`,\n      `robot_id`/`robot_run_id`/`url`), `tag:autogenerated:rebar`, `notify:NONE`.\n- [ ] **Vote → submittability.** A `PASS` gate verdict casts `+MAX` and the change becomes\n      submittable; a `BLOCK` or `INDETERMINATE` verdict casts `-1` and the change is NOT\n      submittable (only a MAX vote enables submit; INDETERMINATE is fail-closed). The full\n      gate-verdict→integer mapping is the table above and is config-driven, not hardcoded.\n- [ ] **Vote-cast failure is fail-closed.** If the REST `review` POST fails (Gerrit\n      4xx/5xx, SSM token fetch/auth failure, or the kernel returns no actionable\n      decision) the change is left NOT submittable (no MAX is ever cast on failure);\n      the failure is logged with the change id and trips the voter alarm. Verified by\n      simulating a Gerrit 503 / a missing token and asserting non-submittable + a log\n      entry + alarm signal.\n- [ ] **Inbound webhook authenticated.** The `webhooks` plugin signs requests with a shared\n      HMAC secret (sourced from SSM); the MCP voter rejects any inbound request whose signature\n      is missing or invalid (verified by replaying a forged/unsigned POST and asserting it is\n      refused and casts no vote).\n- [ ] **Bot identity + least-privilege secret.** The bot account is in `Service Users`\n      (SERVICE_USER tag); its auth token is sourced from SSM via an instance-role policy\n      scoped to the bot-token parameter path only (no `Resource:\"*\"`); re-running\n      `service-user.sh` is idempotent (no duplicate account, no orphaned token).\n- [ ] **Attention-set behavior (derisk).** Verified against the pinned Gerrit 3.14.1\n      that the SERVICE_USER bot is NOT added to the attention set on a non-negative vote\n      and IS (or the required config knob is documented) on a negative vote.\n- [ ] **Plugin provenance (derisk).** The `webhooks` and `events-log` plugins are\n      confirmed to have version-matched, arm64-compatible jars for Gerrit 3.14.1, their\n      licenses vetted, and the exact jar URLs/checksums + install step recorded in\n      `infra/gerrit/` (extends d251 E4; the kernel reviewer stays out of S4).\n- [ ] **Backfill via reconciler (explicit mechanism).** With a `patchset-created`\n      webhook deliberately dropped, the `infra/mcp/reconcile.py` poller — querying\n      `events-log` for patchsets lacking an `LLM-Review` vote and re-invoking the shared\n      voter on its cadence — casts the missing vote within one poll interval, leaving no\n      patchset permanently unreviewed. The events-log plugin alone (a store) does NOT\n      satisfy this.\n- [ ] **Idempotent / deduplicated delivery.** A patchset processed by BOTH the webhook\n      and a backfill pass results in exactly one `LLM-Review` vote and no duplicate\n      robot_comment threads (existing-vote check and/or deterministic `robot_run_id`).\n- [ ] **Fail-closed invariant.** A missed event NEVER yields a submittable-but-unreviewed\n      change; a persistently broken/unavailable voter only delays review — `main` freezes\n      until the voter is restored (no break-glass merge path, per the locked posture).\n- [ ] **Seam documented.** `docs/adr/0001-review-bot-pipe.md` records the bot/label/event\n      contract and the seam b744-WS6 must conform to."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782693728102923001,"uuid":"71eed119-7965-4e24-a192-e8615651edb2"}